timeline
    title Static vs Dynamic Credentials: Exposure Window Comparison

    section STATIC CREDENTIALS (Vulnerable)
        Credential Issued : Credential generated once, stored in vault/env/config
        Time: 0 days
        Day 1-180: Credential in use by application
        Credential Leaked: Day 200 - Attacker gains unauthorized access
        Detection: Day 200 - Credential leak discovered (avg 200 days to detect)
        Incident: Days 200-210 - Attacker has full access during incident response
        Rotation: Day 210+ - Manual rotation across all instances (hours to days of work)
        Access Window: 200+ days of unrestricted attacker access

    section DYNAMIC CREDENTIALS (Secure)
        Credential Issued: Mon - Unique credential generated on-demand, TTL 1 hour
        Credential Used: Mon - Application authenticates to resource
        Credential Leaked: Mon 12:30pm - Attacker obtains the credential
        Credential Expires: Mon 1:00pm - Vault auto-revokes credential from database/IAM
        Attacker Access Revoked: Mon 1:00pm - Stolen credential becomes invalid instantly
        Detection & Response: Mon 1:15pm - Team discovers leak, reviews audit logs
        Access Window: 30 minutes maximum, then self-healing via auto-revocation

    section COMPARISON
        Static Risk: ⚠️ 200+ day exposure window | Manual rotation | Permanent access until remediation
        Dynamic Benefit: ✅ ~1 hour exposure window | Auto-rotation | Self-healing via TTL expiry
        Blast Radius Reduction: 99.9% reduction in exposure time (200 days → 1 hour)
